<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>Which is better — Zapier or Make?</h3>
<p>It depends on your needs. Zapier is a leading choice for beginners and non-technical users who need quick automations with 8,000+ app integrations. Make is a leading choice for technical users who need complex multi-branch workflows, visual scenario building, and substantially lower cost at scale — often one-seventh the price of Zapier for the same volume of executions. Test both free tiers to see which fits your workflow best. <a href="/tool/zapier-central">Read our full Zapier Central review →</a></p>

<h3>Is Make cheaper than Zapier?</h3>
<p>Yes — significantly. At scale, Make costs roughly one-seventh what Zapier does for the same volume of monthly executions. Make's Core plan ($9/month) includes 10,000 operations, while Zapier's equivalent Professional plan covers only 750 tasks at $19.99/month. For a marketing agency running 40,000 monthly operations, Make costs ~$670/year versus Zapier's ~$3,000-4,000/year. However, Make's credit system means AI-heavy operations and frequent polling triggers can increase consumption faster than expected.</p>

<h3>Can Make do everything Zapier can?</h3>
<p>Make can handle more complex workflows than Zapier — including native iterators for array processing, aggregators for data collection, routers for unlimited conditional branching, and per-module error handling with configurable retry logic. However, Zapier offers 8,000+ integrations compared to Make's 3,000+, so niche or regional apps are more likely to be available on Zapier. For mainstream business tools (Google Workspace, Slack, HubSpot, Stripe, Shopify), both platforms cover the essentials well.</p>

<h3>Is Make harder to learn than Zapier?</h3>
<p>Yes — Make has a steeper learning curve. A non-technical user can build their first useful Zap in about 12-15 minutes, while the same user would take 30-45 minutes to build an equivalent scenario in Make's visual canvas. However, Make's flowchart-style editor becomes intuitive once learned and offers substantially more control over complex workflows. For teams with a dedicated automation builder, the initial learning investment pays off through lower cost and greater flexibility.</p>

<h3>Does Zapier or Make have better AI features?</h3>
<p>Both platforms have strong AI capabilities. Zapier offers mature AI integration with 250+ AI tool connectors, AI Agents with MCP, and natural language bot creation through Zapier Central — making AI automation accessible to non-technical users. Make has native AI modules for image recognition, text summarization, and AI agents with autonomous task execution. Zapier wins on breadth and ease of use; Make wins on depth of native AI control for technical teams.</p>

<h3>Can I use both Zapier and Make together?</h3>
<p>Yes — some teams use both. A common setup is using Zapier for simple, high-volume connections that need to be set up quickly by non-technical team members, and Make for complex, cost-sensitive workflows that require advanced logic and data transformation. Since both platforms support webhooks and custom API calls, they can even trigger each other's workflows when needed.</p>

<h3>What's the best free plan for automation?</h3>
<p>Make's free plan is more generous — 1,000 operations per month with multi-step scenarios, compared to Zapier's 100 tasks and single-step Zaps. Make's free tier is actually viable for very small-scale automation, while Zapier's free plan is best viewed as a trial. Both free plans include access to their full app ecosystems, making them equally useful for testing whether a platform meets your needs before committing.</p>

<h2>Final Verdict</h2>
<p>The Zapier vs Make decision comes down to a fundamental trade-off: simplicity vs power, breadth vs depth, convenience vs cost.</p>

<p>Zapier is the safer choice when team skill level is the primary constraint — non-technical users can be productive in minutes, and the 8,000+ app ecosystem means the tool you need is almost certainly already integrated. For small teams under 2,000 monthly tasks, the price difference is small enough that Zapier's ease of use justifies the premium.</p>

<p>Make is the smarter choice when cost, complexity, or volume are the primary drivers. At scale, Make's pricing advantage is decisive — saving agencies and e-commerce stores thousands per year. The visual canvas with native iterators, routers, and per-module error handling makes it a genuinely more capable platform for complex production workflows.</p>

